[1
Date: Wed, 25 Mar 1998 20:13:20 +0000
Subject: About BSE
From: vDedet.pointvet@invivo.edu (Vincent Dedet)

About message "BSE - FRANCE (07)"
be careful, the translation of the French article is not correct (possibly
from an automatic translation) : one striking example : tail (queue) is
translated as neck.
---
Vincent Dedet
DVM, Chief Editor
[to which one might add:
Date: Thu, 26 Mar 1998 08:20:30 -0500 (EST)
From: Ivo Foppa <ifoppa@hsph.harvard.edu
Subject: BSE in France
A really minor detail: "la base de la queue" means the basis of the tail
(not the neck).
Also, I do not think that the pruritus necessarily indicates affection of
the skin, as someone suggested. It is more likely that such intense pruritus
is a neurological manifestation, as well.

Ivo Foppa, M.D.
Harvard School of Public Health
Dept. of Epidemiology
677 Huntington Avenue
Boston, MA 02139
[to which Harriet Meyer <Harriet_Meyer@ama-assn.org (Thu, 26 Mar 1998
10:10:26 -0600) agreed.
***
and
[2
Date: 25 Mar 98 13:38:24 PST
From: Robert.Paul@directory.reed.edu (Robert Paul)

In the provisional English draft of 'Un cas de tremblante sur un boeuf,'
'La demarche etait mal assuree; les membres posterieurs etaient vacillants
et trainaient sur le sol.'
is translated as
'The sequel was assuredly bad; the posterior limbs were flailing about and
pointed skyward.'
It should be:
Its gait was uncertain (or unsteady); its hind legs were wobbly and
dragging on
the ground.
--
Robert Paul
Reed College
robert.paul@reed.edu
