[3
From: Jane_Homan <Jane_Homan@gala.com>
Date: Thu, 26 Mar 1998 09:56:49 -0600
"Manger de la vache enragee" may have a much less sinister derivation. My
tattered recollections of meat inspection suggest that, especially before
uniform humane slaughter methods, an animal which had to be chased around
its pen by its captor -- or vice versa -- would certainly be "stressed ante
mortem" and thus have depleted muscle glycogen, resulting in a poorer rigor
mortis and meat of poor quality and shelf life. Not everything is
microbiology!
--
